aphy and testimony to poetry, essays, chronicles, cinema, literary texts, video, and performance, Samuel Steinberg considers the broad photographic and photopoetic nature of modern witnessing as well as the specific elements of light (gunfire, flares, camera flashes) that ultimately defined the massacre. Steinberg also demonstrates the ways in which the labels of “massacre” and “sacrifice” inform contemporary perceptions of the state’s blatant and violent repression of unrest. With implications for similar processes throughout the rest of Latin America from the 1960s to the present day, Photopoetics at Tlatelolco provides a powerful new model for understanding the intersection of political history and cultural memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aDocumentary filmszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aStudent movementszMexicozMexico CityxHistoryy20th century. 0aTlatelolco Massacre, Mexico City, Mexico, 1968. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30548540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477307496423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477307496/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK